There's something afoot I fear.

author: @midlander8186
text: It's worth mentioning the US credit card clearing companies, MasterCard and Visa, refused to serve anyone but  wealthy and upper middle class customers despite the Indian government's urging them to serve a wider swath of customers.  Then the Indian government provided the impetus for this card.  MasterCard and Visa lost many of their customers and missed out on the broader and still profitable market. MasterCard and Visa then tried to enlist the aid of the US government in an anti-monopolist claim, which failed.  Shame on MasterCard and Visa for trying to strongarm this more democratic finance system after failing to see and serve the broader market.

author: @jasonxeko
text: In a lot of East and Southeast Asian countries they have already developed wallet with very similar capabilities. I was a bit shocked that in the older developed countries, they tend to prefer using cards as their form of cashless payment, while in a lot of the newly developed (and high income developing) countries they tend to prefer someform of QR payment through wallets or bank transfers. I really think this approach is the way to move forward since it is very low cost to implement for many vendors and is generally safer for the user compared to traditional cards. It is great that India has been able to develop such an app that also allows easy transactions.

author: @HarpreetSingh-ke2zk
text:
Many countries have their own e-wallets, which make transactions indeed very easier. 

However, in the future, there is a possibility that these e-wallets will become monopolized and function like bank accounts with a hefty minimum balance requirement. 

Furthermore, these e-wallets may become exclusive to the user's phone, making it impossible to install them on other devices. 

These e-wallets may offer additional facilities and security features, but frequent updates may force users to frequently update or purchase new phones to continue using them.

author: @KarlRock
text: UPI is actually much more than just a digital wallet. The wallet is just the part the consumer sees. UPI (Unified Payment Interface) is actuallyÂ is a real-time payment system developed by the National Payments Corporation of India that facilitates inter-bank transactions. It allows users to transfer money from one bank account to another instantly and securely, without the need for the recipient's bank details like account number or IFSC code.

author: @AkashPatel-lo7vg
text:
I donâ€™t understand why the government should bear the cost of the Merchant Discount Rate (MDR) when businesses themselves benefit from offering payment convenience. Currently, businesses that accept credit and debit card payments are charged up to 2.5% by networks like Visa and MasterCard, whereas UPI transactions typically cost less than 1%. If a merchant processes 30 million in transactions, theyâ€™d pay 750,000 in fees for card payments but only 300,000 for UPI, saving 450,000. Thatâ€™s a substantial benefit for businesses.

Additionally, if a business only offers cash or card payments, it risks losing customers who prefer UPI due to its ease of use, convenience, and cashback incentives. For instance, imagine a store generating 10 lakhs in monthly revenue with an 8% profit margin, yielding 80,000 in profit. If 10% of customers avoid the store because UPI isnâ€™t offered, the business loses 1 lakh in revenue, reducing profit by 8,000. However, if UPI were available, the cost for processing UPI transactions would be just 0.5% of 10 lakhs, or 5,000. In this case, the business would still save 3,000 in profit (8,000 saved from avoided customer loss, minus the 5,000 UPI fee).

This example shows that not offering UPI can result in lost revenue and profits, while adopting it saves money and retains customers. Businesses are ultimately responsible for covering the costs associated with providing convenient payment methods, as they directly benefit from increased sales and customer satisfaction. Expecting the government to cover MDR is unnecessary when merchants stand to gain both loyalty and higher profits by embracing UPI, a more cost-effective payment solution.

author: @abingeorgy3626
text:
Hey, Thank you so much for sharing this video â€“ itâ€™s beautifully made, especially relevant to me as someone in the fintech payments industry. I have a few questions related to real-time P2P transfers (e.g., Google Pay, Zelle, UPI with the support of NCPI):

1. Instant Transfers:
We know that P2P transfers, such as those via Google Pay, Benefit, Zelle, and UPI, are deducted from the sender and credited to the receiver almost immediately. Is this real-time transfer also happening from the senderâ€™s bank to the receiverâ€™s bank like the back end settlements between the banks?

2. Timing of Transfers:
Suppose, we say â€œreal-time backend settlements,â€ what is the actual time frame being referred to?
- Are funds being transferred in true real-time between banks, or is there a delay?

3. Technology Used:
If these transfers are indeed real-time, is blockchain technology involved in UPI or similar systems? 
- If not blockchain, what kind of technology is enabling these rapid transfers?

Comparison with Blockchain:
- If not, how does the technology used in real-time P2P transfers (such as UPI) differ from blockchain technology?

I would appreciate any additional or insights, as I am currently working on a project related to CBDC and would love your input. Iâ€™d also love to engage on a MS teamâ€™s call if needed. Do let me know your thoughts!

Thank you!!

author: @MiscellaneousSounds
text:
As i worked in UPI Project....I'll tell you an interesting part. All this APIs communicate with each other in seconds because they are asynchronous in nature. Also, there are multiple cases where the Reconcilation / Payment status check in case of stuck cases, happens at NPCI network as the NPCI is the mediator between the banks and Payer and Payee. NPCI also takes care of Autopay i,e the UPI mandate which is also a part of UPI flow...but good work buddy keep it going.

Also make sure you don't breach any of the NPCI's policy while sharing the informations on APIs as it could be confidential
